{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "While Don Draper wouldn\u2019t recognize much of today\u2019s advertising business, which is increasingly driven by technology, big personalities at the very top continue to reign.", "abstract": "Television series Mad Men will begin last half of seventh and final season, and while show depicts era of changing advertising industry, some things remain the same; collapse of merger between advertising firms Omnicom Group and Publicis Groupe due to clashing personalities of owners John D Wren and Maurice Levy shows that ego and power still reign in industry, much as they figure greatly in the show.", "section_name": "Business Day", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Emily", "role": "reported", "lastname": "STEEL", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By EMILY STEEL"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/04/business/media/mad-men-and-the-era-that-changed-advertising.html", "lead_paragraph": "While Don Draper wouldn\u2019t recognize much of today\u2019s advertising business, which is increasingly driven by technology, big personalities at the very top continue to reign.", "headline": {"main": "\u2018Mad Men\u2019 and the Era that Changed Advertising", "print_headline": "Changing Course on Madison Ave."}, "_id": "551f376538f0d836f13a250b", "word_count": "1259", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/04/04/business/advertising1/advertising1-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/04/04/business/advertising1/advertising1-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 396, "url": "images/2015/04/04/business/advertising1/advertising1-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/04/04/business/advertising1/advertising1-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "396"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2015/04/04/b